   <section class="pure-u-1 banner-container"> 
    <div class="pure-u-22-24 banner-content"> 
     <h1 class="slogan">How to get data from APIs using Elm</h1> 
     <div class="message"> 
      <p class="post-date">2017-06-30 by Franzé Jr.</p> 
     </div> 
    </div> 
   </section> 
  </div> 
  <div class="pure-g post-recipe _extramargin-bottom"> 
   <section class="post-container pure-u-22-24 pure-u-md-3-5"> 
    <strong>Tagged with</strong> 
    <div class="post-text"> 
     <p><img src="https://dailydrip-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/DailyDrip/blog_posts/elm-for-js-developers-ep-1/elmJS.png" alt=""></p> 
     <p>This is the fourth post in a series of posts about Elm for JavaScript developers. If you're a JavaScript developer, and you want to know more about Elm, stay tuned to this series of posts or sign up for DailyDrip and check out all the episodes we have in our room topic.</p> 
     <p>Here is what we already see:</p> 
     <ul> 
      <li><a href="https://www.dailydrip.com/blog/general-aspects-between-elm-and-js">General Aspects between Elm and JS</a></li> 
      <li><a href="https://www.dailydrip.com/blog/creating-html-elements-and-using-libraries-in-elm">Creating HTML elements and using libraries in Elm</a></li> 
      <li><a href="https://www.dailydrip.com/blog/understanding-the-elm-architecture">Understanding the Elm Architecture</a></li> 
     </ul> 
     <p>You will probably want to work with APIs at some point. How can you get data from an API into your Elm application?</p> 
     <h2 id="what-we-will-build">What we will build</h2> 
     <p>We will build a simple page that shows the current Bitcoin price in USD. We will use the coindesk api to look up the bitcoin price.</p> 
     <p>Here is our API endpoint: <a href="http://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json">http://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json</a>.</p> 
     <p>And our JSON looks like:</p> 
     <pre class="highlight javascript"><code><span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">time</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">{</span>
        <span class="nl">updated</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"Jun 27, 2017 13:25:00 UTC"</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="nx">updatedISO</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"2017-06-27T13:25:00+00:00"</span><span class="p">,</span>
        <span class="nx">updateduk</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"Jun 27, 2017 at 14:25 BST"</span>
<span class="p">},</span>
<span class="nx">disclaimer</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"This data was produced from the CoinDesk Bitcoin Price Index (USD). Non-USD currency data converted using hourly conversion rate from openexchangerates.org"</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="nx">chartName</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"Bitcoin"</span><span class="p">,</span>
<span class="nx">bpi</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">USD</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">{</span>
            <span class="nl">code</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"USD"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">symbol</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"&amp;#36;"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"2,415.8175"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">description</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"United States Dollar"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate_float</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mf">2415.8175</span>
    <span class="p">},</span>
    <span class="nx">GBP</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">{</span>
            <span class="nl">code</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"GBP"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">symbol</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"&amp;pound;"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"1,893.1433"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">description</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"British Pound Sterling"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate_float</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mf">1893.1433</span>
    <span class="p">},</span>
    <span class="nx">EUR</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="p">{</span>
            <span class="nl">code</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"EUR"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">symbol</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"&amp;euro;"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"2,142.2407"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">description</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="s2">"Euro"</span><span class="p">,</span>
            <span class="nx">rate_float</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="mf">2142.2407</span>
        <span class="p">}</span>
    <span class="p">}</span>
<span class="p">}</span>
</code></pre> 
     <p>In our JSON structure, we have the time and the current conversion for USD, EUR and GBP.</p> 
     <h2 id="creating-our-elm-app">Creating our Elm app</h2> 
     <p>To create an Elm project</p> 
     <pre class="highlight shell"><code>mkdir bitcoin-price
<span class="nb">cd </span>bitcoin-price
</code></pre> 
     <p>And then we can create our Elm code.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight shell"><code>vim Main.elm
</code></pre> 
     <p>Let's start creating a Hello World app, using the Elm Html package.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="kr">module</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Hello</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">exposing</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(..)</span><span class="w"> </span>import <span class="kt">Html</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">exposing</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span>text<span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span>main <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>text <span class="s">"Hello World"</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <p>To run it, you can use elm-reactor and this will make our Elm app works in the port 8000.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight shell"><code>?  bitcoin-price elm-reactor
elm-reactor 0.18.0
Listening on http://localhost:8000
</code></pre> 
     <p>You should see Hello World in your screen.</p> 
     <p>Now we have our app working. Let's try to get the data from our API!</p> 
     <h2 id="using-decoders">Using Decoders</h2> 
     <p>One of the cool things about Elm is there way it handles JSON decoders. Elm provides a clean, declarative way to specify how to turn json into typed data. </p> 
     <p>Personally, I'm using this approach and <a href="https://www.dailydrip.com/blog/using-decoders-in-your-api-the-boundary-between-two-worlds.html">I posted about it before</a>.</p> 
     <p>If we check the Elm documentation - and you always should - we can see the function <code class="prettyprint">at</code>. This is used to specify a path in the json structure, and specify the way to parse the data you find there. </p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">decodeContent :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Decoder</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span>decodeContent <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>at <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"bpi"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"USD"</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"rate"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span>string
</code></pre> 
     <p>In this function, we are getting the value at the <code class="prettyprint">bpi</code> key, then inside that we find the <code class="prettyprint">USD</code> key, and then the <code class="prettyprint">rate</code> key. We then parse this as a string. Our <code class="prettyprint">decodeContent</code> is a Json decoder that decided a String. This string will be our bitcoin price.</p> 
     <p>In our case, our model will be just an Elm record that contains the <code class="prettyprint">currentPrice</code>, and it is a string.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="kr">type</span><span class="w"> </span>alias <span class="kt">Model</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nf">currentPrice :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <h2 id="our-elm-program">Our Elm Program</h2> 
     <p>We are going to use <code class="prettyprint">Html.program</code>, because we need to have side effects, commands. The commands will be our Http requests.</p> 
     <p>Here we will have an init function, update, our view and subscriptions. We will not have subscriptions for the moment, this will be covered in another blog post.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">main :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Program</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Never</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Model</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span>main <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Html</span><span class="p">.</span>program
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span>init <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>init
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>update <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>update
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>view <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>view
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>subscriptions <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>always <span class="kt">Sub</span><span class="p">.</span>none
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <h2 id="our-messages">Our Messages</h2> 
     <p>Messages in the Elm architecture describe all of the things that can happen in our app. In our case, we will have three messages:</p> 
     <ul> 
      <li>GotBitcoinPrice: We will send this message when we just got the return from our api, and we will update our model.</li> 
      <li>GetBitcoinPrice: We will send this message when we want to get the API request.</li> 
      <li>NoOp: When we will do nothing.</li> 
     </ul> 
     <p>Let's define our Messages.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="kr">type</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">GotBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kt">Result</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Http</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="kt">Error</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">GetBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">NoOp</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <h2 id="our-init-function">Our init function</h2> 
     <p>Our init function will call the update function by passing the <code class="prettyprint">GetBitcoinPrice</code>.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">init :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Model</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span>init <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>update <span class="kt">GetBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span>currentPrice <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"Not yet!"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <p>Let's check our update function.</p> 
     <h2 id="our-update-function">Our Update Function</h2> 
     <p>Our update function will update our model with the current bitcoin price.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">update :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Model</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Model</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span>update msg model <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">case</span><span class="w"> </span>msg <span class="nb">of</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">NoOp</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span>model<span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="p">.</span>none<span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">GetBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span>model<span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Http</span><span class="p">.</span>send <span class="kt">GotBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span>getBitcoinPrice <span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">GotBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span>result <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">case</span><span class="w"> </span>result <span class="nb">of</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Err</span><span class="w"> </span>httpError <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">let</span><span class="w"> </span>_ <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Debug</span><span class="p">.</span>log <span class="s">"handleBitcoinPriceError"</span><span class="w"> </span>httpError
<span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">in</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span>model<span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="p">.</span>none <span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Ok</span><span class="w"> </span>price <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span>model <span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span>currentPrice <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>price <span class="p">},</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="p">.</span>none <span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <p>In our update function, we are handling our Messages. If we have <code class="prettyprint">GetBitcoinPrice</code>, we will call <a href="http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/http/1.0.0/Http#send"><code class="prettyprint">Http.send</code></a> with two arguments: our GotBitcoinPrice and the request returned by our function getBitcoinPrice.</p> 
     <p>To understand it more, let's see what the Http.send method is:</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">send :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kt">Result</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Error</span><span class="w"> </span>a <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span>msg<span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Request</span><span class="w"> </span>a <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="w"> </span>msg
</code></pre> 
     <p>It receives two arguments: - (Result Error a -&gt; msg) - Request a</p> 
     <p>And it returns a Command msg. Now, let's see the implementation of our functions:</p> 
     <ul> 
      <li>GotBitcoinPrice (Result Http.Error String)</li> 
      <li>getBitcoinPrice : Http.Request String</li> 
     </ul> 
     <p>As you can see, it matches the definition of our <code class="prettyprint">Http.send</code> method and it should be fine. Every time you don't understand a type annotation in Elm, go to the documentation and you will probably understand it better.</p> 
     <p>Once we get the price, we will have the <code class="prettyprint">GotBitcoinPrice</code> message. This can have as result an error or not. If we got an error, in this case an <code class="prettyprint">httpError</code>, we will just log using <code class="prettyprint">Debug.log</code>. In case everything is fine, we will update our model’s <code class="prettyprint">currentPrice</code> field.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">GotBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span>result <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">case</span><span class="w"> </span>result <span class="nb">of</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Err</span><span class="w"> </span>httpError <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">let</span><span class="w"> </span>_ <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Debug</span><span class="p">.</span>log <span class="s">"handleBitcoinPriceError"</span><span class="w"> </span>httpError
<span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">in</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span>model<span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="p">.</span>none <span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Ok</span><span class="w"> </span>price <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span>model <span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span>currentPrice <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>price <span class="p">},</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Cmd</span><span class="p">.</span>none <span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <h2 id="our-function-get">Our function get</h2> 
     <p>As our last function we will talk about, we have our <code class="prettyprint">getBitcoinPrice</code>. This function describes the Http request, using <a href="http://package.elm-lang.org/packages/elm-lang/http/1.0.0/Http#get">get</a>. It doesn't make the request: the runtime does that when it receives a command. We use <code class="prettyprint">Http.send</code> later to turn this request into a command.</p> 
     <p>Let's see its type annotation:</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">get :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Decoder</span><span class="w"> </span>a <span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Request</span><span class="w"> </span>a
</code></pre> 
     <p>It receives a string and a Decoder. This is exactly what we are doing. We have our <code class="prettyprint">api</code> function returning our <code class="prettyprint">URL</code> and we already saw our <code class="prettyprint">decodeContent</code> function.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">api :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span>api <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"http://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nf">getBitcoinPrice :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Http</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="kt">Request</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span>getBitcoinPrice <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Http</span><span class="p">.</span>get api decodeContent
</code></pre> 
     <h2 id="styling-our-component">Styling our component</h2> 
     <p>Let's use <a href="https://github.com/rundis/elm-bootstrap/"><code class="prettyprint">elm-bootstrap</code></a> to make our page look like better!</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">view :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Model</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Html</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span>view model <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Grid</span><span class="p">.</span>container <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>class <span class="s">"text-center jumbotron"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- Responsive fixed width container</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>CDN<span class="p">.</span>stylesheet <span class="c1">-- Inlined Bootstrap CSS for use with reactor</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>mainContent model
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <p>Our mainContent will be centered. Here we are using Bootstrap buttons and classes.</p> 
     <pre class="highlight elm"><code><span class="nf">mainContent :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">{</span><span class="w"> </span>a <span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nf">currentPrice :</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">String</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Html</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Msg</span><span class="w"> </span>mainContent model <span class="o">=</span><span class="w"> </span>div <span class="p">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>p <span class="p">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>h1 <span class="p">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>text <span class="s">"Bitcoin Price"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">],</span><span class="w"> </span>h5 <span class="p">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>text <span class="s">"It costs right now:"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>p <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>class <span class="s">"alert alert-success"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>h4 <span class="p">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>text model<span class="p">.</span>currentPrice<span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>text <span class="s">" USD"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Button</span><span class="p">.</span>button
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Button</span><span class="p">.</span>outlinePrimary
<span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Button</span><span class="p">.</span>attrs <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>onClick <span class="kt">GetBitcoinPrice</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>text <span class="s">"Update it now"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span>div <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>class <span class="s">"text-right small"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>a <span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>href <span class="s">"https://github.com/dailydrip/elm-bitcoin-price"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="w"> </span>text
<span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"Source Code"</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span></code></pre> 
     <h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2> 
     <p>Today we saw how to get data from an API in Elm. We used the notion of Decoders. We saw what our resulting Elm Program looks like. You can use a similar thing to work with any API you want.</p> 
     <p><img src="https://dailydrip-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/DailyDrip/blog_posts/howt-get-data-from-apis-usin-elm/Screenshot.png" alt=""></p>
